    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The interest calculation on your student loan is a process that always applies to the remaining principal balance.  Each month, the lender calculates the interest charge based on what you *still owe* from the previous month. Because the interest accrues on the outstanding balance, a larger balance means a larger interest payment, which is why it feels like you're just paying the interest before much of your payment can reduce the principal.\n\nThink of it this way: your monthly payment is divided into two parts—one goes to interest, and the rest goes to the principal. In the early stages of a loan, the interest portion is usually much larger than the principal portion. As you pay down the principal, the base amount the interest is calculated on gets smaller, and then more of your payment starts going toward the actual loan amount.",
