    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, i guess. but it still feels super unfair. it's like there's this hidden cost that just eats up my money before i even get a chance to pay down the debt. like, even when I try to pay a little extra, the interest calculation still feels like it's working against me to keep the balance high. is there a mathematical reason why it's so hard to gain momentum on the principal at the start?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's not a hidden cost, but rather the mathematical nature of compound interest applied to debt, which is a very common feature of lending. The reason it feels so slow at the beginning is because the interest is calculated on the *entire* original loan amount for many months. Every time you pay, a small piece goes to principal, but the interest is still calculated on that large, nearly unchanged balance.\n\nThis initial drag is why many financial experts recommend making extra payments as soon as possible; those extra dollars go straight to the principal, immediately lowering the base upon which future interest is calculated. A smaller principal means less interest next month, creating a faster snowball effect toward paying off the debt.",
