    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get that, it's just frustrating. it basically feels like the interest is this invisible force that's actively fighting against my progress. every time i think i'm making a dent, the math just pulls me back. is there any way to actually see how much of my total lifetime payments is going to interest versus principal, or is it just something you have to accept as a sunk cost?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You absolutely do not have to just accept it as a sunk cost; you can track it precisely! Most amortization schedules, or detailed loan payoff calculators, provide a breakdown showing exactly how much of each payment goes to interest versus principal over time. This visualization is key to understanding the long-term impact.\n\nIf you want a clearer picture, look for a \"total interest paid\" projection in your loan documents or use an online calculator where you input your loan terms. Seeing that total figure laid out—how much went to the lender versus how much actually bought you the money—is very clarifying. It helps transform that abstract \"invisible force\" into a concrete, quantifiable number.",
